The latest MSTest is **v4.0.0**. Here are the breaking changes relevant to your code:

### 1. `[ExpectedException]` is removed (affects 2 of your tests)

This is the biggest impact. Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()`:

```csharp
// Before
[ExpectedException(typeof(ArgumentNullException))]
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Validate(null);
}

// After
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => Validate(null));
}
```

### 2. Other notable v4 breaking changes (not affecting your current code, but good to know)

| Change | Impact |
|---|---|
| `Assert.ThrowsException` removed | Use `Assert.ThrowsExactly` instead |
| `Assert` message + `params object[]` overloads removed | Use string interpolation for messages |
| `ClassCleanupBehavior` enum removed | `[ClassCleanup]` now always runs end-of-class |
| `TestTimeout` enum removed | Use `[Timeout(int.MaxValue)]` instead |
| `TestContext.Properties` is now `IDictionary<string, object>` | Use `.ContainsKey()` not `.Contains()` |
| `TestContext.ManagedType` removed | Use `FullyQualifiedTestClassName` |
| Dropped .NET < 8 support | Your `net8.0` target is fine |
| Several analyzers promoted to warnings | May surface new warnings |

### Want me to apply the fix?

I can upgrade your `.csproj` to MSTest 4.0.0 and migrate the `[ExpectedException]` usages to `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()`. Just say the word.
